721814f-a.title: Manhattan: Mulberry Street - Prince Street.
721814f-a.text:
Mulberry Street, at, adjoining and north of the N. W. corner
of Prince Street (left), showing prominently an old residence there.
The corner structure is No. 47 Prince Street, while it's prototype
is No 259 Mulberry Street. Adjoining the latter is a three story
frame dwelling with a brick front. This is No. 261 Mulberry Street.
October 22, 1935
Berenice Abbott, photo
Federal Art Project
NO REPRODUCTIONS

721815f-b.title: Manhattan: Mulberry Street - Prince Street
721815f-b.text:
Mulberry Street, west side, north from and including Prince, to and
including Jersey Streets, showing prominently No. 47 Prince Street, a
3-story house, at the N.W. corner. Other buildings on this block bear
Nos. 259, 261, 263-5 and 267 all on Mulberry Street. No. 261 is a 3-story
frame house with a brick front. Shown on the left are the lower stories
of a 6-story tenement house, No. 49-51 Prince Street. This set consists
of 2 views.
1922.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collectfon.
MAY BE REPRODUCED.

721816f-a.title: Manhattan: Mulberry Street - Prince Street
721816f-a.text:
Mulberry Street, at the N.E. corner of Prince Street, showing St.
Patrick's R. C. Church. The cornerstone of this structure, formerly
The Cathedral, was laid June 8, 1809 and consecrated by Bishop Cheverus
of Boston, on May 4, 1815; it being completed in the latter year. In
the churchyard is the tomub of Valentine Sherry. Here also are buried
Francis Delmonico and Stephen Jumel.
February 1924.
Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.
MAY BE REPRODUCED.
